Split¶

Let's be quick and split the data before we get any insight, change anything that we couldn't have changed if we didn't look at the test data, it's a good practice too if the DataViz part is done after as you might get thoughts of modeling technqiue based on the test data added (Do that only if you have very short amount of data)

————————————————————————¶

Important Note¶

This type of split is to simulate a real life example, the idea is to split Temporally-Based even though we're not going to be able to test the 11th, and 12th month, this is a bad split if only we had more data to teach the model at least twice on these missing months in the test set.

We will split the values in order of their dates as if we are validating on the present, training on the past, and testing on the future

————————————————————————¶

Filling the NaNs¶

We can go with either a fixed value as 0, statistical value as the mean or mode, algorithmic values as KNN or MICE

In this case, 0 gives the intuition to the algorithm the nearly 5000 Dept. (More than half) has not done any marketing campains which is completely false and misleading!

An algorithmic value is a good choice but the problem is that about 60% of the data are missing, this gives us the idea that there might be more missing data in the future and applying an algorithm at that time will make the model suffer.

Best and a "good enough effectiveness" can be gotten from applying the mean and giving a fair advantage of the lost cells. This is done after splitting the data so that we don't introduce any data leakages (distributional leakages). We will have to store the mean

def makeLineplot(data, groubed_by_x, title,  y_label= 'Weekly Sales', 
                 hue_order = ['Weekly_Sales'], fix_ticks_num=True, rotate=True ):
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(17,8))
    sns.lineplot(x=groubed_by_x, y='value', hue='variable', data=pd.melt(data, [groubed_by_x]), estimator=None,
                palette = 'Set1', hue_order=hue_order)

    ax.axes.set_title(title,fontsize=18)
    ax.set_xlabel(groubed_by_x,fontsize=15)
    ax.set_ylabel(y_label,fontsize=15)
    ax.tick_params(labelsize=12.5)
    if(fix_ticks_num):
        ax.set_xticks(ticks=data.index.unique().tolist()[2::3], minor=False)
    else:
        ax.set_xticks(ticks=data.index.unique().tolist(), minor=False)
        
    plt.legend()
    if(rotate):
        plt.setp( ax.xaxis.get_majorticklabels(), rotation=-45, ha="left", rotation_mode="anchor");

Insights¶

  • UMAP: Very smooth and nice seperation between the distributional quantile classes of weekly sales, but keep in mind that this is a supervised technique, but remember that the reduction of test data will try to transform each value to it's closest number as illustrated, then a regression ML model can be used after

  • PCA there're some very weak and not clear clusters in the data and it doesn't look promising

Modeling¶

Models¶

  1. DummyRegressor Our Base-Line
  1. KNeighborsRegressor It might be very suitable to work with quantile clusters produced by UMAP reduced features
  1. LGBMRegressor There are many outliers in the dataset which will surely be falsely predicted by the classifier. A gradient boosting algorithm that gives a higher weight for false predictions is a good one to go with as the model might underfit the whole dataset due to abundance of outliers and extremes.
  1. RandomForestRegressor Bagging can solve any overfitting that a model on this dataset might fall into due to the skewness of the dataset.

Basically: LGBM is to solve underfitting which is not strongly likely to happen as the model might overfit and the skewed partition and predicts everything to be a low value disregarding that there are extremes sometimes. Hence RFG is to solve this issue of overfitting due to bootstrapping and aggregation of multiple DT's (Decision Trees are going to be our weak learners).

  1. VotingRegressor To combine the best two

Quality Metrics¶

  1. MAE (Mean Absolute Error) We have a highly right-skewed dataset with too many extremes and outliers. We need a metric that is not very sensitive to outliers
  1. R-Squared/Coefficient of Determination To know how much of the response variable's variance is explained by the regression model.
  1. Time-series plot of predictions vs truths To account for any wrong patterns or flaws that the model might be following
  1. Residual Plot To account for the possible misleading explanation of R-Squared value caused by continuous response variable prediction over/under-estimates, bias, or residual pattern

def tuner_trainer(model, X_train, y_train, params):
    pipeline = Pipeline([
            ('scale', StandardScaler()),
            ('regre', model)])

    tscv = TimeSeriesSplit(n_splits = 5)
    grid = GridSearchCV(pipeline, param_grid = params, cv=tscv, 
                        n_jobs=-1, refit=True, scoring='neg_mean_absolute_error', verbose=True)
    grid.fit(X_train, y_train)
    
    
    X_train_sc = pd.DataFrame(StandardScaler().fit_transform(X_train.values), 
                              columns=X_train.columns, 
                              index=X_train.index.tolist())
    model = grid.best_estimator_.fit(X_train_sc, y_train)
    return {
        "model": model,
        "best_params": grid.best_params_,
        "best_score": grid.best_score_
    }

def evaluate(indicies, y_train, y_train_preds, y_test, y_test_preds, res_plot=True, time_plot=True):
    
    if (time_plot):
        data = pd.DataFrame({
            "y_test": y_test, 
            "y_test_preds": y_test_preds,
            "Date": indicies
        }).set_index('Date').groupby('Date').mean()

        data = pd.DataFrame(StandardScaler().fit_transform(data.values), 
                                         columns=data.columns, index=data.index)
        
        data['Date'] = data.index.tolist()


        makeLineplot(data = data, groubed_by_x='Date',
                     title="Weekly Sales Truth vs Predictions", 
                     hue_order=['y_test', 'y_test_preds'], fix_ticks_num=False);
    if(res_plot):
        fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(17, 6))
        residuals = np.asarray(y_test - y_test_preds)
        residuals = StandardScaler().fit_transform(residuals.reshape(-1, 1))
        residuals = np.squeeze(residuals)
        y_test_scaled = StandardScaler().fit_transform(y_test_preds.reshape(-1, 1).tolist())
        y_test_scaled = np.squeeze(y_test_scaled)
        sns.residplot(y_test_scaled, residuals, color=(1, 0, 0, 0.3))
    
    return {
        "mae_train": mean_absolute_error(y_train_preds, y_train),
        "r2_train": r2_score(y_train_preds, y_train),
        "mae_test": mean_absolute_error(y_test, y_test_preds),
        "r2_test": r2_score(y_test, y_test_preds)
    }

Final Notes¶

  1. KNR is always overfitting on values less than 500. Of course if I had more memory on my machine, I would've gone for more than $\sqrt{n}$ But my machine's memory cannot hold.
  2. We can clearly see that has averged between RF Regressor and LGBM models and got a middle ground on the training set but then achieved the highest on the test set
  3. Keep in mind that MAE, MSE, RMSE are used for two reasons, a comparison between other models, as well as an indicator of the model's quality in hand. Now, the second can be tricky, the value of MAE depends on the business, environment, and the relative dataset distribution and descriptive statistics. To explain the last one with a very loose example: if 0 < Weekly Sales < 1,000 range of values, an MAE of 10 is similar to 1000 if 0 < Weekly Sales < 100,000. This is a weak example as of course you need to think about the mean, std., and distributional curve
  4. Some of the lower performance achieving models have a very well meaningful residual plot which illustrate a clear trend in errors, this is why we use risedual plots with $R^2$ measurement. In order not to be fooled by $R^2$
